english:
  title: Three Poems in the Ancient Style
  author: Seong Hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Before the pavilion stands a wondrous tree,
    Its emerald leaves so lush and verdant—
    Yet autumn wind comes whispering, caressing,
    And falling dew has dimmed its flowering beauty.
    From western hills a flock of birds descends,
    Day after day they flutter down to nest,
    But the solitary phoenix, broken-winged,
    Is granted not a single branch to rest upon.
    Yet bloom and fade each have their destined hour—
    Why curse the hardship that befalls us all?

    Today this feast gathers noble company,
    Distinguished guests fill the great hall,
    Delicate dishes gleam on jeweled stands,
    Green wine overflows in golden cups.
    On left and right sit beauties of renown,
    Their graceful brows and eyes so clear and bright.
    Slowly they raise their milky arms
    To pluck the lute and sound the cosmic notes—
    But years spin like wheels that turn and pass,
    And suddenly our temples frost with age.
    We meet: let us rejoice while we are here,
    What use in sorrow's cry?
    Those nobles bedecked with rank and honor
    Must all return at last to northern grave.

    I wade the river to gather lotus blooms,
    Climb mountains high to pluck the ivy vines.
    Their shadows flutter, swaying in the wind,
    Their fragrance clings sweet upon my sleeves—
    I wish to send these gifts to my beloved,
    And wait for him beyond the clouds.
    But clouds grow deep, my love does not appear,
    So where shall these longing eyes now turn?

    How brilliant shines the moon, so pure and bright!
    Its radiance seeks the recluse in hiding.
    That recluse bears ten thousand griefs within,
    And sits in sorrow through the endless night.
    Leaves stir and whisper in the wind-swept trees,
    Stars glitter scattered through the vast expanse.
    A wanderer adrift at heaven's edge,
    A solitary soul confined within these walls.
    I cannot weave the threads of sleep,
    Yet seek to cross—alas, no ferry waits.
  footnotes:
    - This work is titled 'Imitation of Ancients' (擬古), a classical Chinese poetic form where later poets compose verses in the style and manner of celebrated ancient works, often engaging with themes of transience, courtly life, and the melancholy of unfulfilled longing.
    - The 'solitary phoenix' (孤鸞) is a classical metaphor for one isolated or unable to find one's place in the world.
    - The 'northern grave' (北邙) refers to the burial grounds north of Luoyang, used as a metonym for death and the final resting place of all people regardless of rank.
    - 'The poem moves through three distinct movements: temporal decay and misfortune, courtly pleasure and its evanescence, and finally romantic longing and melancholic isolation.'
